TypeScript supports several access modifiers to control the visibility and accessibility of class members (properties and methods). These are:

Public: This is the default access level. Public members are accessible from anywhere without any restrictions. They can be accessed from outside the class, from derived classes, and within the class itself.

typescript

Copy code

class Example {
  public publicProperty: string;
}
Private: Private members are accessible only within the class that defines them. They cannot be accessed from outside of the class or by derived classes.

typescript

Copy code

class Example {
  private privateProperty: string;
}
Protected: Protected members are accessible within the class and by classes that are derived from it. However, they are not accessible from outside these classes.

typescript

Copy code

class Example {
  protected protectedProperty: string;
}
Readonly: This is not exactly an access modifier but a modifier that can be used in conjunction with the above access modifiers. It makes a property read-only, meaning it can be assigned a value only during declaration or within the constructor of the same class.

typescript

Copy code

class Example {
  readonly readonlyProperty: string;
}

Creating objects in TypeScript can be done in several ways, similar to JavaScript, but with the added benefit of type annotations for enforcing the structure of the objects.
Example:

typescript

Copy code

type User = {
    name: string;
    age: number;
};

let user: User = {
    name: "Alice",
    age: 25
};

You can specify the target ECMAScript version by configuring the tsconfig.json file. Set the target property to es5 to ensure TypeScript transpiles the code to ES5, which is compatible with older browsers.

json

Copy code

{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "target": "es5",
    "module": "commonjs",
