In TypeScript, both interfaces and type aliases are used to define custom data types, but they have some differences:
Syntax:
Interface: Interfaces are defined using the interface keyword. They describe the shape of an object or class.
Type Alias: Type aliases are defined using the type keyword. They can represent any type, not just objects, and are more flexible.
Extending/Implementing:
Interface: Interfaces can be extended by other interfaces using the extends keyword, and classes can implement interfaces.
Type Alias: Type aliases cannot be extended or implemented. They are standalone and represent specific types.
Compatibility:
Interface: Interfaces are open-ended by default. If you declare an interface with a certain structure, you can later add more properties to it without causing issues.
Type Alias: Type aliases create exact types. Once defined, you cannot add or change properties to the type without breaking compatibility.
Union and Intersection:
Interface: Interfaces are not suitable for creating union or intersection types directly.
Type Alias: Type aliases can be used to create union types (|) and intersection types (&) more easily.
Example:

typescript

Copy code

// Interface
interface Person {
    name: string;
    age: number;
}

// Extending an interface
interface Employee extends Person {
    employeeId: string;
}

// Type alias
type Person = {
    name: string;
    age: number;
};

// Creating a union type with a type alias
type StringOrNumber = string | number;

A type guard is a TypeScript function or expression that checks and narrows down the type of a value within a certain code block.
Common type guards include typeof, instanceof, and custom user-defined functions.

typescript

Copy code

function isString(value: any): value is string {
  return typeof value === "string";
}

let data: any = "Hello, TypeScript!";
if (isString(data)) {
  // TypeScript knows 'data' is a string here.
  console.log(data.length);
}

In TypeScript, class constants can be implemented using static readonly modifiers. These modifiers are used together to create properties that are constant at the class level. This means they belong to the class itself rather than to instances of the class, and their values cannot be altered once set.
Example:

typescript

Copy code

class MyClass {
    static readonly CONSTANT_NAME: Type = value;
}

console.log(MyClass.CONSTANT_NAME);
static means the property belongs to the class itself, not to instances of the class.
readonly ensures that the property's value cannot be changed after its initial assignment.
CONSTANT_NAME is the name of your constant. By convention, constants are often written in uppercase.
Type is the TypeScript type of the constant (like number, string, boolean, etc.).
value is the value assigned to the constant.

The never type represents values that never occur. It's often inferred in situations like functions that throw errors or enter infinite loops.
Practical use cases include exhaustive checking in discriminated unions and functions that never return (e.g., an exception-throwing function).
Example:

typescript

Copy code

// Functions that never return
function throwError(message: string): never {
    throw new Error(message);
}

function infiniteLoop(): never {
    while (true) {}
}

In TypeScript, mapped types are a powerful feature that allow you to create new types by transforming or modifying the properties of existing types.
Mapped types are particularly useful for generating new types based on existing ones, often used for scenarios like creating read-only versions of objects, optionalizing properties, or changing property types.
Mapped types are defined using the keyof and in keywords in combination with type operations.
Example:

typescript

Copy code

type MappedType = {
    [Property in SourceType]: NewType;
};
Property: This represents the name of the property in the resulting type.
SourceType: This is the type whose properties you want to transform or modify.
NewType: This specifies the new type of the property in the resulting type.

TypeScript uses async and await to work with asynchronous operations in a more readable and structured manner.
async is used to define a function that returns a promise, and await is used to pause the execution of a function until the promise is resolved.

typescript

Copy code

async function fetchData() {
  const response = await fetch('https://api.example.com/data');
  const data = await response.json();
  return data;
}

In TypeScript, void is a type that represents the absence of any value. It is commonly used as the return type of functions that do not return a value. In other words, if a function is intended to perform an action but not return anything, you would annotate it with void.
The most common use of void is as the return type for functions that do not return anything. For example:

typescript

Copy code

function logMessage(message: string): void {
    console.log(message);
}

Optional chaining in TypeScript is a language feature that allows for safe navigation of nested object properties or method calls by using the ?. operator.
It addresses the issue of potentially encountering null or undefined values when accessing properties or calling methods on objects. With optional chaining, if any part of the chain is null or undefined, the expression short-circuits, and the result is also null or undefined, preventing runtime errors.

typescript

Copy code

const person = {
    name: 'Alice',
    address: {
        city: 'New York',
        zipcode: '10001'
    }
};

const city = person.address?.city; // Safe access, city will be 'New York'
const country = person.address?.country; // Safe access, country is undefined

Mixins in programming, including in TypeScript, are a design pattern that allows you to create classes which combine behaviors or functionalities from multiple parent classes or objects. They are used to overcome the limitations of single inheritance by enabling a form of multiple inheritance or composition. Mixins allow you to "mix in" additional properties or methods into a class.
Example:

typescript

Copy code

// A mixin function that adds a timestamp to a class
function Timestamped<T extends { new (...args: any[]): {} }>(Base: T) {
    return class extends Base {
        timestamp = Date.now();
    };
}

// A base class
class User {
    name: string;
    constructor(name: string) {
        this.name = name;
    }
}

// Creating a class from a mixin
const TimestampedUser = Timestamped(User);

// Using the new class
const user = new TimestampedUser("Alice");
console.log(user.name);       // Alice
console.log(user.timestamp);  // A timestamp value

In this example, the Timestamped function is a mixin that adds a timestamp property to any class. It is used to create a new class TimestampedUser which has both the properties and methods of User as well as the added timestamp property from the mixin.

The keyof keyword in TypeScript is used to create a union type of all possible keys in an object type. It's often used to create type-safe code when working with object properties.

typescript

Copy code

interface Person {
  name: string;
  age: number;
}

type PersonKeys = keyof Person; // "name" | "age"

Discriminated unions, also known as tagged unions or algebraic data types, are a TypeScript and programming language feature that allows you to create complex type structures by combining multiple types into a single type.
Discriminated unions are distinguished by a shared property called a discriminant, which helps TypeScript determine which specific type within the union is currently in use.
Example:

typescript

Copy code

type Shape = {
    kind: 'circle';
    radius: number;
} | {
    kind: 'rectangle';
    width: number;
    height: number;
};

function getArea(shape: Shape): number {
    switch (shape.kind) {
        case 'circle':
            return Math.PI * shape.radius ** 2;
        case 'rectangle':
            return shape.width * shape.height;
        default:
            // TypeScript ensures all cases are handled
            const exhaustiveCheck: never = shape;
            return exhaustiveCheck;
    }
}
In this example, the Shape type is a discriminated union consisting of two variants: circle and rectangle. The kind property serves as the discriminant. The getArea function uses a switch statement to determine the specific type within the union based on the kind property and calculates the area accordingly.

The non-nullable assertion operator (!) in TypeScript tells the compiler that a variable or property is guaranteed to be non-null or non-undefined, even if the compiler cannot infer it. It should be used with caution when you're certain that a value won't be null or undefined to avoid runtime errors.

typescript

Copy code

function greet(name: string | null): string {
    // Use the non-nullable assertion operator to assert that 'name' is not null
    return `Hello, ${name!}!`; // 'name!' asserts that 'name' is not null
}

const result1 = greet("Alice"); // Valid, 'name' is a non-null string
const result2 = greet(null);    // Valid, but potentially risky

Recursive types in TypeScript are types that refer to themselves in their own definition. They are often used to model data structures like trees or linked lists. Here's an example of a recursive type for a binary tree:
Example:

typescript

Copy code

type TreeNode<T> = {
  value: T;
  left?: TreeNode<T>;
  right?: TreeNode<T>;
};

Type predicates in TypeScript are functions that assert the type of a value and narrow it down within the function's scope. They are often used with the is keyword to check if a value matches a specific type.

typescript

Copy code

function isString(value: any): value is string {
  return typeof value === 'string';
}

if (isString(someValue)) {
  // 'someValue' is now recognized as 'string' type.
  console.log(someValue.length);
}

The noImplicitAny flag in TypeScript is a compiler option that, when enabled, ensures that the type any is not implicitly assigned to variables, parameters, and function return types when their type is not explicitly declared and cannot be inferred from the context. The primary purpose of this flag is to enforce stronger type checking, thereby catching potential errors or ambiguities in the code at compile time.

typescript

Copy code

// Without noImplicitAny
function add(a, b) {
    return a + b;
}

// With noImplicitAny
function add(a, b) {
    return a + b; // Error: Parameter 'a' implicitly has an 'any' type.
}

The Partial utility type in TypeScript allows you to create a new type that makes all properties of an existing type optional. It's often used when you want to create partial objects that may not have all required properties.

typescript

Copy code

interface User {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  email: string;
}

type PartialUser = Partial<User>;

const partialUser: PartialUser = {
  name: 'John',
};

The Omit utility type is used to create a new type by excluding specific properties from an existing type. It allows you to create a type that has all the properties of the original type except for the ones you specify to be omitted.

typescript

Copy code

type Person = {
  name: string;
  age: number;
  address: string;
};

type PersonWithoutAge = Omit<Person, 'age'>;

Contextual typing in TypeScript refers to the TypeScript compiler's ability to infer the type of an expression based on its context. This means the context in which a value is used can influence its type without the need for explicit type annotations. This feature is particularly useful for making the code more concise and readable while still benefiting from TypeScript's strong typing capabilities.

typescript

Copy code

interface Event {
    message: string;
}

function handleEvent(event: Event) {
    console.log(event.message);
}

// In a callback, TypeScript knows the type of 'e' is Event
document.addEventListener("click", (e) => handleEvent(e));

In TypeScript, a scope variable's accessibility is determined by where it is declared, which can either be within a specific block (local scope) or outside any block (global scope). Local scope variables, declared within functions or blocks using let or const, are accessible only within those blocks and cannot be accessed from outside.
Global scope variables, declared outside any function or block, are accessible from any part of the program. TypeScript, following JavaScript's scoping rules, allows for clear and manageable variable scopes to prevent naming conflicts and unintended interactions.

typescript

Copy code

let globalVar = "Accessible globally";

function testScope() {
    let localVar = "Accessible only in this function";
    console.log(globalVar); // Works fine
    console.log(localVar);  // Works fine
}

testScope();
console.log(globalVar);   // Works fine
console.log(localVar);    // Error: localVar is not defined outside testScope

String literal types in TypeScript allow you to create types that accept only specific string values. They are defined using string literal values as type annotations.

typescript

Copy code

type Fruit = 'apple' | 'banana' | 'orange';

function eat(fruit: Fruit): void {
  console.log(`Eating a ${fruit}`);
}

eat('apple'); // Valideat('grape'); // Error: Argument of type '"grape"' is not assignable to parameter of type 'Fruit'.

Key remapping in mapped types allows you to create a new type by transforming or renaming the keys of an existing type. It's achieved by using the in keyword and defining new keys.
Example:

typescript

Copy code

type RenameKeys<T> = {
  [K in keyof T as `new_${K}`]: T[K];
};

type Original = { foo: string; bar: number };
type Renamed = RenameKeys<Original>; // { new_foo: string; new_bar: number }

Declaration files (.d.ts) in TypeScript are used to declare the types and interfaces for external JavaScript libraries or modules that lack type definitions. They provide type information for TypeScript when working with JavaScript code.
Example:

typescript

Copy code

// math-lib.d.tsdeclare module 'math-lib' {
  export function add(x: number, y: number): number;
  export function subtract(x: number, y: number): number;
}

The as const assertion in TypeScript is used to create read-only literal types from values. It tells TypeScript to infer the most specific literal type for the expression.
Example:

typescript

Copy code

const colors = ['red', 'green', 'blue'] as const;
// 'colors' is of type: ['red', 'green', 'blue']

function getColor(color: typeof colors[number]) {
  // 'color' can only be one of the literal values in 'colors'
  return color;
}

An anonymous function in TypeScript, as in JavaScript, is a function that is defined without a name. Anonymous functions are often used in situations where a function is used as an argument to another function, or assigned to a variable, and a name is not needed or would not add clarity to the code. They are commonly used in callbacks, event handlers, and with promises.

typescript

Copy code

// Example using an arrow function:
let myFunction = () => {
    console.log("Hello from an anonymous function!");
};

In TypeScript, getters and setters are special methods used to read and modify the properties of an object. They provide a way to define accessors on object properties, allowing for more controlled and flexible property access and mutation.

typescript

Copy code

class Person {
    private _name: string;

    get name(): string {
        return this._name;
    }

    set name(newName: string) {
        if (newName.length > 0) {
            this._name = newName;
        }
    }
}

let person = new Person("Alice");
person.name = "Bob"; // Changed using setter

Internal (File-Level) Modules:
Introduction: Internal modules are created using TypeScript's module system within a single TypeScript file. They provide a way to encapsulate related code within the file itself. Internal modules are also referred to as "file-level modules" or "namespaces."
Syntax: Internal modules are defined using the namespace keyword (or using the ES6 module syntax), and code within them is encapsulated.

typescript

Copy code

// Internal module (namespace) example
namespace MyNamespace {
    export function greet(name: string) {
        console.log(`Hello, ${name}!`);
    }
}
External (Ambient) Modules:
Introduction: External modules are used to organize code across multiple files and are more commonly used in modern TypeScript projects. They are also known as "ambient modules" or "ES6 modules."
Syntax: External modules use the export and import keywords to define and import code from other files.

typescript

Copy code

// ModuleA.ts
export const message = "Hello from ModuleA";

// ModuleB.ts
import { message } from "./ModuleA";
console.log(message); // "Hello from ModuleA"

In TypeScript, namespaces (formerly known as "internal modules") are a way to encapsulate and organize related code within a single file or across multiple files.
Namespaces provide a level of modularity and prevent naming conflicts by allowing you to group related functions, classes, variables, or other code constructs under a common namespace name.
Example:

typescript

Copy code

// Definition
namespace MyNamespace {
    export function someFunction() {
        // ...
    }
}

// Usage
MyNamespace.someFunction();

In TypeScript, extends is used for class inheritance, allowing a class to inherit properties and methods from another class, thereby establishing a subclass-superclass relationship. In contrast, implements is used when a class wants to adhere to the structure defined by an interface, ensuring that it implements all the properties and methods of the interface.

typescript

Copy code

// Using extends for inheritance
class Animal {
    eat() { console.log("Eating"); }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    bark() { console.log("Woof!"); }
}

// Using implements for interface adherence
interface Movable {
    move(): void;
}

class Car implements Movable {
    move() { console.log("Car is moving"); }
}

A symbol in TypeScript (and JavaScript) is a unique and immutable primitive value used primarily as a key for object properties to avoid name collisions. Each time a symbol is created, it is distinct from other symbols, even if they have the same description.
Symbols are created using the Symbol() function and can be used to define object properties that are not easily accessible or overridden by other code.

typescript

Copy code

let myUniqueKey = Symbol("unique_property");
let myObject = {
    [myUniqueKey]: "This is a unique property"
};

console.log(myObject[myUniqueKey]); // Outputs: "This is a unique property"

A generic type in TypeScript is a type that can work with multiple data types while preserving type safety. It allows you to create functions, classes, or interfaces that can operate on values of different types without knowing those types in advance.
Generic types are defined using a placeholder type parameter enclosed in angle brackets (<T> by convention), which represents the actual type that will be provided when the generic type is used.
Example:

typescript

Copy code

function swap<T>(a: T, b: T): [T, T] {
    return [b, a];
}

const [x, y] = swap(10, 20); // x is 20, y is 10
const [str1, str2] = swap("Hello", "World"); // str1 is "World", str2 is "Hello"
